  "why": "HCGPE is used as a gel polymer electrolyte for Li metal batteries. Reported properties directly for HCGPE include: ionic conductivity 4.8 mS cm^-1 at 30°C and lower activation energy 0.16 eV vs HCE 0.18 eV, indicating easier Li+ migration (Results: “The ionic conductivity of HCGPE reaches 4.8 mS cm^-1 at 30°C… the activation energy of the HCGPE (0.16 eV) is lower than that of the HCE (0.18 eV)”). Li-ion transference number tLi+ = 0.56 for HCGPE (Results: “the tLi+ of HCGPE (0.56) is slightly higher than the HCE (0.48)”). Oxidative behavior: HCGPE shows an oxidation peak at ≈3.9 V and enhanced oxidation stability vs HCE (Results: “HCGPE shows an oxidation peak at ≈3.9 V… HCE shows a lower onset oxidation potential compared to HCGPE”). Application performance in cells is shown for systems employing HCGPE with separators: Li/Cu CE ≈99.3% for HCGPE-PE and 98.45% for HCGPE-PP; Li/Li symmetric cycling stable >950 h at 2.0 mA cm^-2 / 1.0 mAh cm^-2 for HCGPE-PE; full-cell Li/NCM811 with thin Li shows 91% capacity retention over 200 cycles with HCGPE-PE. These cell results involve HCGPE integrated with specific separators (PE or PP)."
}

